# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: capacitive-sensing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] The capacitance between two conductors depends on the opposing surface area of the conductors, the distance between those conductors, and the permittivity of any dielectric material between them.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] For many dielectric materials, the permittivity, and thus the capacitance, is independent of the potential difference between the conductors and the total charge on them.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] The SI unit of capacitance is the farad (symbol: F), named after the English physicist Michael Faraday.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] A 1 farad capacitor, when charged with 1 coulomb of electrical charge, has a potential difference of 1 volt between its plates.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] The reciprocal of capacitance is called elastance.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] In discussing electrical circuits, the term *capacitance* is usually a shorthand for the mutual capacitance between two adjacent conductors, such as the two plates of a capacitor.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] However, every isolated conductor also exhibits capacitance, here called *self-capacitance*.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] It is measured by the amount of electric charge that must be added to an isolated conductor to raise its electric potential by one unit of measurement, e.g., one volt.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] The reference point for this potential is a theoretical hollow conducting sphere, of infinite radius, with the conductor centered inside this sphere.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] The inter-winding capacitance of a coil is sometimes called self-capacitance, but this is a different phenomenon.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] It is actually mutual capacitance between the individual turns of the coil and is a form of stray or parasitic capacitance.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] This self-capacitance is an important consideration at high frequencies: it changes the impedance of the coil and gives rise to parallel resonance.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] In many applications this is an undesirable effect and sets an upper frequency limit for the correct operation of the circuit.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] A common form is a parallel-plate capacitor, which consists of two conductive plates insulated from each other, usually sandwiching a dielectric material.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] In a parallel plate capacitor, capacitance is very nearly proportional to the surface area of the conductor plates and inversely proportional to the separation distance between the plates.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] The discussion above is limited to the case of two conducting plates, although of arbitrary size and shape.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] The definition $C=Q/V$ does not apply when there are more than two charged plates, or when the net charge on the two plates is non-zero.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] To handle this case, James Clerk Maxwell introduced his *coefficients of potential*.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] If three (nearly ideal) conductors are given charges $Q_{1},Q_{2},Q_{3}$ , then the voltage (actually potential) at conductor 1 is given by $V_{1}=P_{11}Q_{1}+P_{12}Q_{2}+P_{13}Q_{3},$ and similarly for the other voltages.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] Hermann von Helmholtz and Sir William Thomson showed that the coefficients of potential are symmetric, so that $P_{12}=P_{21}$ , etc.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] Similarly, the charge can be written in terms of voltages (actually potentials): $Q_{1}=C_{11}V_{1}+C_{12}V_{2}+C_{13}V_{3},$ The collection of coefficients $C_{ij}={\frac {\partial Q_{i}}{\partial V_{j}}}$ is known as the *capacitance matrix*,.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] In open systems which are not charge neutral, so that field lines can end at infinity (which is implicitly assumed to have 0 potential in the above equations), the capacitance and elastance matrices are inverses of each other: $C^{-1}=P$ .
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] In closed systems however the capacitance matrix is singular (it has a 0 eigenvalue due to charge neutrality), and so formally the elastance matrix as the inverse of the capacitance matrix is ill defined; it would require independently varying the charges.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] Since no actual device holds perfectly equal and opposite charges on each of the two "plates", it is the mutual capacitance that is reported on capacitors.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] The capacitance of the majority of capacitors used in electronic circuits is generally several orders of magnitude smaller than the farad.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] The most common units of capacitance are the microfarad (μF), nanofarad (nF), picofarad (pF), and, in microcircuits, femtofarad (fF).
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] Some applications also use supercapacitors that can be much larger, as much as hundreds of farads, and parasitic capacitive elements can be less than a femtofarad.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] Historical texts use other, obsolete submultiples of the farad, such as "mf" and "mfd" for microfarad (μF); "mmf", "mmfd", "pfd", "μμF" for picofarad (pF).
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] The capacitance can be calculated if the geometry of the conductors and the dielectric properties of the insulator between the conductors are known.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] Capacitance is proportional to the area of overlap and inversely proportional to the separation between conducting sheets.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] The closer the sheets are to each other, the greater the capacitance.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] An example is the capacitance of a capacitor constructed of two parallel plates both of area ${\textstyle A}$ separated by a distance ${\textstyle d}$ .
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] The equation is a good approximation if *d* is small compared to the other dimensions of the plates so that the electric field in the capacitor area is uniform, and the so-called *fringing field* around the periphery provides only a small contribution to the capacitance.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] Any two adjacent conductors can function as a capacitor, though the capacitance is small unless the conductors are close together for long distances or over a large area.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] This (often unwanted) capacitance is called parasitic or stray capacitance.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] Stray capacitance can allow signals to leak between otherwise isolated circuits (an effect called crosstalk), and it can be a limiting factor for proper functioning of circuits at high frequency.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] Stray capacitance between the input and output in amplifier circuits can be troublesome because it can form a path for feedback, which can cause instability and parasitic oscillation in the amplifier.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] It is often convenient for analytical purposes to replace this capacitance with a combination of one input-to-ground capacitance and one output-to-ground capacitance; the original configuration – including the input-to-output capacitance – is often referred to as a pi-configuration.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] Since impedance varies inversely with capacitance, the internode capacitance, *C*, is replaced by a capacitance of KC from input to ground and a capacitance of ⁠(*K* − 1)*C*/*K*⁠ from output to ground.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] When the input-to-output gain is very large, the equivalent input-to-ground impedance is very small while the output-to-ground impedance is essentially equal to the original (input-to-output) impedance.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] Calculating the capacitance of a system amounts to solving the Laplace equation ${\textstyle \nabla ^{2}\varphi =0}$ with a constant potential ${\textstyle \varphi }$ on the 2-dimensional surface of the conductors embedded in 3-space.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] There is no solution in terms of elementary functions in more complicated cases.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] For plane situations, analytic functions may be used to map different geometries to each other.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] The energy (measured in joules) stored in a capacitor is equal to the *work* required to push the charges into the capacitor, i.e. to charge it.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] Consider a capacitor of capacitance *C*, holding a charge +*q* on one plate and −*q* on the other.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] The energy stored in a capacitor is found by integrating this equation.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] The capacitance of nanoscale dielectric capacitors such as quantum dots may differ from conventional formulations of larger capacitors.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] In particular, the electrostatic potential difference experienced by electrons in conventional capacitors is spatially well-defined and fixed by the shape and size of metallic electrodes in addition to the statistically large number of electrons present in conventional capacitors.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] In nanoscale capacitors, however, the electrostatic potentials experienced by electrons are determined by the number and locations of all electrons that contribute to the electronic properties of the device.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] In such devices, the number of electrons may be very small, so the resulting spatial distribution of equipotential surfaces within the device is exceedingly complex.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] The capacitance of a connected, or "closed", single-electron device is twice the capacitance of an unconnected, or "open", single-electron device.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] whose energy terms may be obtained as solutions of the Schrödinger equation.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] This expression of "quantum capacitance" may be written as $C_{Q}(N)={e^{2} \over U(N)},$ which differs from the conventional expression described in the introduction where $W_{\text{stored}}=U$ , the stored electrostatic potential energy, $C={Q^{2} \over 2U},$ by a factor of ⁠1/2⁠ with $Q=Ne$ .
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] which is appropriate since $\mathrm {d} q=0$ for systems involving either many electrons or metallic electrodes, but in few-electron systems, $\mathrm {d} q\to \Delta \,Q=e$ .
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] The integral generally becomes a summation.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] One may trivially combine the expressions of capacitance $Q=CV$ and electrostatic interaction energy, $U=QV,$ to obtain $C=Q{1 \over V}=Q{Q \over U}={Q^{2} \over U},$ which is similar to the quantum capacitance.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] A more rigorous derivation is reported in the literature.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] In particular, to circumvent the mathematical challenges of spatially complex equipotential surfaces within the device, an *average* electrostatic potential experienced by each electron is utilized in the derivation.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] Apparent mathematical differences may be understood more fundamentally.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] The potential energy, $U(N)$ , of an isolated device (self-capacitance) is twice that stored in a "connected" device in the lower limit $N=1$ .
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] In nanoscale devices such as quantum dots, the "capacitor" is often an isolated or partially isolated component within the device.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] The primary differences between nanoscale capacitors and macroscopic (conventional) capacitors are the number of excess electrons (charge carriers, or electrons, that contribute to the device's electronic behavior) and the shape and size of metallic electrodes.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] In nanoscale devices, nanowires consisting of metal atoms typically do not exhibit the same conductive properties as their macroscopic, or bulk material, counterparts.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] In electronic and semiconductor devices, transient or frequency-dependent current between terminals contains both conduction and displacement components.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] Conduction current is related to moving charge carriers (electrons, holes, ions, etc.), while displacement current is caused by a time-varying electric field.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] Carrier transport is affected by electric fields and by a number of physical phenomena - such as carrier drift and diffusion, trapping, injection, contact-related effects, impact ionization, etc.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] As a result, device admittance is frequency-dependent, and a simple electrostatic formula for capacitance $C=q/V,$ is not applicable.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] A more general definition of capacitance, encompassing electrostatic formula, is: $C={\frac {\operatorname {Im} (Y(\omega ))}{\omega }},$ where $Y(\omega )$ is the device admittance, and $\omega$ is the angular frequency.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] In general, capacitance is a function of frequency.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] At high frequencies, capacitance approaches a constant value, equal to "geometric" capacitance, determined by the terminals' geometry and dielectric content in the device.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] A paper by Steven Laux presents a review of numerical techniques for capacitance calculation.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] Usually, capacitance in semiconductor devices is positive.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] However, in some devices and under certain conditions (temperature, applied voltages, frequency, etc.), capacitance can become negative.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] Non-monotonic behavior of the transient current in response to a step-like excitation has been proposed as the mechanism of negative capacitance.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] Negative capacitance has been demonstrated and explored in many different types of semiconductor devices.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] A capacitance meter is a piece of electronic test equipment used to measure capacitance, mainly of discrete capacitors.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] For most purposes and in most cases the capacitor must be disconnected from circuit.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] Many DVMs (digital volt meters) have a capacitance-measuring function.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] These usually operate by charging and discharging the capacitor under test with a known current and measuring the rate of rise of the resulting voltage; the slower the rate of rise, the larger the capacitance.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] DVMs can usually measure capacitance from nanofarads to a few hundred microfarads, but wider ranges are not unusual.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] It is also possible to measure capacitance by passing a known high-frequency alternating current through the device under test and measuring the resulting voltage across it (does not work for polarised capacitors).
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] More sophisticated instruments use other techniques such as inserting the capacitor-under-test into a bridge circuit.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] By varying the values of the other legs in the bridge (so as to bring the bridge into balance), the value of the unknown capacitor is determined.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] This method of *indirect* use of measuring capacitance ensures greater precision.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitance] Through the use of Kelvin connections and other careful design techniques, these instruments can usually measure capacitors over a range from picofarads to farads.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] In electrical engineering, **capacitive sensing** (sometimes **capacitance sensing**) is a technology, based on capacitive coupling, that can detect and measure anything that is conductive or has a dielectric constant different from air.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Many types of sensors use capacitive sensing, including sensors to detect and measure proximity, pressure, position and displacement, force, humidity, fluid level, and acceleration.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Human interface devices based on capacitive sensing, such as touchpads, can be used in place of a computer mouse.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Digital audio players, mobile phones, and tablet computers will sometimes use capacitive sensing touchscreens as input devices.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Capacitive sensors can also replace mechanical buttons.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] A capacitive touchscreen typically consists of a capacitive touch sensor along with at least two complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor (CMOS) integrated circuit (IC) chips, an application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) controller and a digital signal processor (DSP).
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Capacitive sensing is commonly used for mobile multi-touch displays, popularized by Apple's iPhone in 2007.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Capacitive sensors are constructed from many different media, such as copper, indium tin oxide (ITO) and printed ink.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Copper capacitive sensors can be implemented on standard FR4 PCBs as well as on flexible material.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] ITO allows the capacitive sensor to be up to 90% transparent (for one layer solutions, such as touch phone screens).
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Size and spacing of the capacitive sensor are both very important to the sensor's performance.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] In addition to the size of the sensor, and its spacing relative to the ground plane, the type of ground plane used is very important.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Since the parasitic capacitance of the sensor is related to the electric field's (E-field) path to ground, it is important to choose a ground plane that limits the concentration of E-field lines with no conductive object present.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Designing a capacitance sensing system requires first picking the type of sensing material (FR4, Flex, ITO, etc.).
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] One also needs to understand the environment the device will operate in, such as the full operating temperature range, what radio frequencies are present and how the user will interact with the interface.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Tools such as CapExt, ANSYS Q3D Extractor, and solutions from FastFieldSolvers can be employed to optimize designs by enhancing sensitivity, accurately modeling electromagnetic fields, and improving performance across varying environmental conditions.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] 2. self-capacitance, where the object (such as a finger) loads the sensor or increases the parasitic capacitance to ground.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] In both cases, the difference of a preceding absolute position from the present absolute position yields the relative motion of the object or finger during that time.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] The technologies are elaborated in the following section.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] In this basic technology, only one side of the insulator is coated with conductive material.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] A small voltage is applied to this layer, resulting in a uniform electrostatic field.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] When a conductor, such as a human finger, touches the uncoated surface, a capacitor is dynamically formed.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Because of the sheet resistance of the surface, each corner is measured to have a different effective capacitance.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] The sensor's controller can determine the location of the touch indirectly from the change in the capacitance as measured from the four corners of the panel: the larger the change in capacitance, the closer the touch is to that corner.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] With no moving parts, it is moderately durable, but has low resolution, is prone to false signals from parasitic capacitive coupling, and needs calibration during manufacture.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Therefore, it is most often used in simple applications such as industrial controls and interactive kiosks.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Projected capacitance touch (PCT) technology is a capacitive technology which allows more accurate and flexible operation, by etching the conductive layer.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] An X-Y grid is formed either by etching one layer to form a grid pattern of electrodes, or by etching two separate, parallel layers of conductive material with perpendicular lines or tracks to form the grid; comparable to the pixel grid found in many liquid crystal displays (LCD).
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] The greater resolution of PCT allows operation with no direct contact, such that the conducting layers can be coated with further protective insulating layers, and operate even under screen protectors, or behind weather and vandal-proof glass.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Because the top layer of a PCT is glass, PCT is a more robust solution versus resistive touch technology.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Depending on the implementation, an active or passive stylus can be used instead of or in addition to a finger.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] This is common with point of sale devices that require signature capture.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Gloved fingers may not be sensed, depending on the implementation and gain settings.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Conductive smudges and similar interference on the panel surface can interfere with the performance.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Such conductive smudges come mostly from sticky or sweaty finger tips, especially in high humidity environments.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Collected dust, which adheres to the screen because of moisture from fingertips can also be a problem.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] There are two types of PCT: self capacitance, and mutual capacitance.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Capacitance is typically measured indirectly, by using it to control the frequency of an oscillator, or to vary the level of coupling (or attenuation) of an AC signal.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Either this charging time or voltage can be a predetermined constant.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] For instance, if measuring after a constant amount of time, then the capacitance can be determined using only the final voltage.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Alternatively if using a fixed threshold voltage, then instead only need to measure the charging time duration to reach that voltage threshold.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] This step response measurement can be continually repeated (e.g. by using a square wave).
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] For an example capacitive sense IC, Texas Instruments's FDC1004 applies a 25-kHz step waveform to charge up an electrode, and after a defined amount of time, converts the analog voltage representing that charge into a digital value of capacitance using a built-in analog-to-digital converter (ADC).
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] The design of a simple capacitance meter is often based on a relaxation oscillator.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] The capacitance to be sensed forms a portion of the oscillator's RC circuit or LC circuit.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] The capacitance can be calculated by measuring the charging time required to reach the threshold voltage (of the relaxation oscillator), or equivalently, by measuring the oscillator's frequency.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Both of these are proportional to the RC (or LC) time constant of the oscillator circuit.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Another measurement technique is to apply a fixed-frequency AC-voltage signal across a capacitive divider (a voltage divider that uses capacitors instead of resistors).
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] This consists of two capacitors in series, one of a known value and the other of an unknown value.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] An output signal is then taken from across one of the capacitors.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] The value of the unknown capacitor can be found from the ratio of capacitances, which equals the ratio of the output/input signal amplitudes, as could be measured by an AC voltmeter.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] More accurate instruments may use a capacitance bridge configuration, similar to a Wheatstone bridge.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] The capacitance bridge helps to compensate for any variability that may exist in the applied signal.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] While not specific to capacitive sensing, charge transfer uses a switched capacitor network to accumulate charge onto an integrating capacitor over a series of discrete steps, to produce an accurate sum of all the individual charge contributors.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Delta-sigma modulation can also measure capacitance instead of voltage.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] The primary source of error in capacitance measurements is stray capacitance, which if not guarded against, may fluctuate between roughly 10 pF and 10 nF.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] The stray capacitance can be held relatively constant by shielding the (high impedance) capacitance signal and then connecting the shield to (a low impedance) ground reference.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Also, to minimize the unwanted effects of stray capacitance, it is good practice to locate the sensing electronics as near the sensor electrodes as possible.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Capacitive touchscreens are more responsive than resistive touchscreens (which react to any object since no capacitance is needed).
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] However, projective capacitance improves a touchscreen's accuracy as it forms a triangulated grid around the point of touch.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] A standard stylus cannot be used for capacitive sensing, but special capacitive styli, which are conductive, exist for the purpose.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] These special styli used to be more expensive to purchase, but the cost of this technology has fallen greatly and capacitive styli are now widely available for a nominal charge, and are sometimes given away for free with mobile accessories.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] They consist of an electrically conductive shaft with a soft conductive rubber tip, thereby resistively connecting the fingers to the tip of the stylus.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] One can even make a capacitive stylus by wrapping conductive material, such as anti-static conductive film, around a standard stylus or by rolling the film into a tube.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Some capacitative touchscreens cannot be used with gloves and can fail to sense correctly with even a small amount of water on the screen.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] The capacitive touchscreens used to be more expensive to manufacture than resistive touchscreens.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Mutual capacitive sensors can provide a two-dimensional image of the changes in the electric field.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Using this image, a range of applications have been proposed.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Authenticating users, estimating the orientation of fingers touching the screen and differentiating between fingers and palms become possible.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] While capacitive sensors are used for the touchscreens of most smartphones, the capacitive image is typically not exposed to the application layer.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Power supplies with a high level of electronic noise can reduce accuracy.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Many stylus designs for resistive touchscreens will not register on capacitive sensors because they are not conductive.
[src:capacitive-sensing/capacitive-sensing] Styluses that work on capacitive touchscreens primarily designed for fingers are required to simulate the difference in dielectric offered by a human finger.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] A **tactile sensor** is a device that measures information arising from physical interaction with its environment.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] Tactile sensors are generally modeled after the biological sense of cutaneous touch which is capable of detecting stimuli resulting from mechanical stimulation, temperature, and pain (although pain sensing is not common in artificial tactile sensors).
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] Tactile sensors are used in robotics, computer hardware and security systems.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] A common application of tactile sensors is in touchscreen devices on mobile phones and computing.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] Tactile sensors may be of different types including piezoresistive, piezoelectric, optical, capacitive and elastoresistive sensors.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] Tactile sensors appear in everyday life such as elevator buttons and lamps which dim or brighten by touching the base.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] Sensors that measure very small changes must have very high sensitivities.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] Sensors need to be designed to have a small effect on what is measured; making the sensor smaller often improves this and may introduce other advantages.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] Tactile sensors can be used to test the performance of all types of applications.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] For example, these sensors have been used in the manufacturing of automobiles (brakes, clutches, door seals, gasket), battery lamination, bolted joints, fuel cells etc.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] Tactile imaging, as a medical imaging modality, translating the sense of touch into a digital image is based on the tactile sensors.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] Tactile imaging closely mimics manual palpation, since the probe of the device with a pressure sensor array mounted on its face acts similar to human fingers during clinical examination, deforming soft tissue by the probe and detecting resulting changes in the pressure pattern.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] Robots designed to interact with objects requiring handling involving precision, dexterity, or interaction with unusual objects, need sensory apparatus which is functionally equivalent to a human's tactile ability.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] Tactile sensors have been developed for use with robots.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] Tactile sensors can complement visual systems by providing added information when the robot begins to grip an object.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] At this time vision is no longer sufficient, as the mechanical properties of the object cannot be determined by vision alone.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] Determining weight, texture, stiffness, center of mass, curvature, coefficient of friction, and thermal conductivity require object interaction and some sort of tactile sensing.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] Several classes of tactile sensors are used in robots of different kinds, for tasks spanning collision avoidance and manipulation.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] Some methods for simultaneous localization and mapping are based on tactile sensors.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] Pressure sensor arrays are large grids of tactels.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] Each tactel is capable of detecting normal forces.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] Tactel-based sensors provide a high resolution 'image' of the contact surface.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] Alongside spatial resolution and force sensitivity, systems-integration questions such as wiring and signal routing are important.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] Pressure sensor arrays are available in thin-film form.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] They are primarily used as analytical tools used in the manufacturing and R&D processes by engineers and technicians, and have been adapted for use in robots.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] Examples of such sensors available to consumers include arrays built from conductive rubber, lead zirconate titanate (PZT), polyvinylidene fluoride(PVDF), PVDF-TrFE, FET, and metallic capacitive sensing elements.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] Several kinds of tactile sensors have been developed that take advantage of camera-like technology to provide high-resolution data.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] A key exemplar is the Gelsight technology first developed at MIT which uses a camera behind an opaque gel layer to achieve high-resolution tactile feedback.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] The Samsung "See-through-your-skin" (STS) sensor uses a semi-transparent gel to produce combined tactile and optical imaging.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] Strain gauges rosettes are constructed from multiple strain gauges, with each gauge detecting the force in a particular direction.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] When the information from each strain gauge is combined, the information allows determination of a pattern of forces or torques.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] A variety of biologically inspired designs have been suggested ranging from simple whisker-like sensors which measure only one point at a time through more advanced fingertip-like sensors, to complete skin-like sensors as on the latest iCub.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] Biologically inspired tactile sensors often incorporate more than one sensing strategy.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] For example, they might detect both the distribution of pressures, and the pattern of forces that would come from pressure sensor arrays and strain gauge rosettes, allowing two-point discrimination and force sensing, with human-like ability.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] Advanced versions of biologically designed tactile sensors include vibration sensing which has been determined to be important for understanding interactions between the tactile sensor and objects where the sensor slides over the object.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] Such interactions are now understood to be important for human tool use and judging the texture, even curvature, of an object.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] One such sensor combines force sensing, vibration sensing, and heat transfer sensing.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] A bioinspired tactile sensor lets robots "feel" their surroundings with 1.76° precision, enabling blind navigation (0.2mm accuracy) and texture recognition (97% success).
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] Its robust design withstands extreme deformations for reliable operation in real-world environments.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] Recently, a sophisticated tactile sensor has been made open-hardware, enabling enthusiasts and hobbyists to experiment with an otherwise expensive technology.
[src:capacitive-sensing/tactile-sensor] Furthermore, with the advent of cheap optical cameras, novel sensors have been proposed which can be built easily and cheaply with a 3D printer.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] A **touchscreen** (or **touch screen**) is a type of display that can detect touch input from a user to do a specific task.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] It consists of both an input device (a touch panel) and an output device (a visual display).
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The touch panel is typically layered on the top of the electronic visual display of a device.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Touchscreens are commonly found in smartphones, tablets, laptops, and other electronic devices.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The display is often an LCD, AMOLED or OLED display.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] A person can give input or control the information processing system through simple or multi-touch gestures by touching the screen with a special stylus or one or more fingers.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Some touchscreens use ordinary or specially coated gloves to work, while others may only work using a special stylus or pen.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The user can use the touchscreen to react to what is displayed and, if the software allows, to control how it is displayed; for example, zooming to increase the text size.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] A touchscreen allows users to interact directly with on-screen content, rather than using indirect input devices such as a mouse or touchpad.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Touchscreens are commonly found on smartphones, tablets, kiosks, and many modern laptops, where they allow tapping, swiping, and pinching to perform actions on the screen.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Touchscreens are common in devices such as smartphones, handheld game consoles, and personal computers.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] They are common in point-of-sale (POS) systems, automated teller machines (ATMs), electronic voting machines, and automobile infotainment systems and controls.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] They can also be attached to computers or, as terminals, to networks.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] They play a prominent role in the design of digital appliances such as personal digital assistants (PDAs) and some e-readers.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Touchscreens are important in educational settings such as classrooms or on college campuses.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The popularity of smartphones, tablets, and many types of information appliances has driven the demand and acceptance of common touchscreens for portable and functional electronics.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Touchscreens are found in the medical field, heavy industry, automated teller machines (ATMs), and kiosks such as museum displays or room automation, where keyboard and mouse systems do not allow a suitably intuitive, rapid, or accurate interaction by the user with the display's content.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Historically, the touchscreen sensor and its accompanying controller-based firmware have been made available by a wide array of after-market system integrators, and not by display, chip, or motherboard manufacturers.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Display manufacturers and chip manufacturers have acknowledged the trend toward acceptance of touchscreens as a user interface component and have begun to integrate touchscreens into the fundamental design of their products.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] One predecessor of the modern touchscreen includes stylus based systems.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] A patent was filed by Philco Company for a stylus designed for sports telecasting which, when placed against an intermediate cathode-ray tube (CRT) display would amplify and add to the original signal.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Effectively, this was used for temporarily drawing arrows or circles onto a live television broadcast, as described in US 2487641A, Denk, William E, "Electronic pointer for television images", issued 8 November 1949 .
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The first version of a touchscreen which operated independently of the light produced from the screen was patented by AT&T Corporation US 3016421A, Harmon, Leon D, "Electrographic transmitter", issued 9 January 1962 .
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] This touchscreen utilized a matrix of collimated lights shining orthogonally across the touch surface.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] When a beam is interrupted by a stylus, the photodetectors which no longer are receiving a signal can be used to determine where the interruption is.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Later iterations of matrix based touchscreens built upon this by adding more emitters and detectors to improve resolution, pulsing emitters to improve optical signal to noise ratio, and a nonorthogonal matrix to remove shadow readings when using multi-touch.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Later inventions built upon this system to free telewriting styli from their mechanical bindings.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Graham patented an “indirect” light-pen telewriting apparatus that allowed users to draw on a separate surface while the system electronically transmitted and reproduced the strokes on a computer display.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] This design reduced mechanical limitations of earlier stylus-based systems and demonstrated an early form of electronic handwriting capture, enabling drawings and annotations to be stored or transmitted for later use.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The first finger driven touchscreen was developed by Eric Johnson, of the Royal Radar Establishment located in Malvern, England, who described his work on capacitive touchscreens in a short article published in 1965 and then more fully—with photographs and diagrams—in an article published in 1967.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Another precursor of touchscreens, an ultrasonic-curtain-based pointing device in front of a terminal display, had been developed by a team around Rainer Mallebrein at Telefunken *Konstanz* for an air traffic control system.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] In 1970, this evolved into a device named "Touchinput-*Einrichtung*" ("touch input facility") for the SIG 50 terminal utilizing a conductively coated glass screen in front of the display.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] This was patented in 1971 and the patent was granted a couple of years later.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The same team had already invented and marketed the *Rollkugel* mouse RKS 100-86 for the SIG 100-86 a couple of years earlier.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The application of touch technology for air traffic control was described in an article published in 1968.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Frank Beck and Bent Stumpe, engineers from CERN (European Organization for Nuclear Research), developed a transparent touchscreen in the early 1970s, based on Stumpe's work at a television factory in the early 1960s.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Then manufactured by CERN, and shortly after by industry partners, it was put to use in 1973.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] A group at the University of Illinois filed for a patent on an optical touchscreen that became a standard part of the Magnavox Plato IV Student Terminal and thousands were built for this purpose.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] These touchscreens had a crossed array of 16×16 infrared position sensors, each composed of an LED on one edge of the screen and a matched phototransistor on the other edge, all mounted in front of a monochrome plasma display panel.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] This arrangement could sense any fingertip-sized opaque object in close proximity to the screen.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] In 1973, Beck and Stumpe published another article describing their capacitive touchscreen.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] This indicated that it was capable of multi-touch but this feature was purposely inhibited, presumably as this was not considered useful at the time ("A...variable...called BUT changes value from zero to five when a button is touched.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The touching of other buttons would give other non-zero values of BUT but this is protected against by software" (Page 6, section 2.6).
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] "Actual contact between a finger and the capacitor is prevented by a thin sheet of plastic" (Page 3, section 2.3).
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] An American company, Elographics – in partnership with Siemens – began work on developing a transparent implementation of an existing opaque touchpad technology, U.S. patent No.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] 3,911,215, 7 October 1975, which had been developed by Elographics' founder George Samuel Hurst.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The resulting resistive technology touch screen was first shown on the World's Fair at Knoxville in 1982.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Multi-touch technology began in 1982, when the University of Toronto's Input Research Group developed the first human-input multi-touch system, using a frosted-glass panel with a camera placed behind the glass.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] An optical touchscreen was used on the HP-150 starting in 1983.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The HP 150 was one of the world's earliest commercial touchscreen computers.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] HP mounted their infrared transmitters and receivers around the bezel of a 9-inch Sony cathode ray tube (CRT).
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Bob Boie of AT&T Bell Labs, used capacitance to track the mechanical changes in thickness of a soft, deformable overlay membrane when one or more physical objects interact with it; the flexible surface being easily replaced, if damaged by these objects.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The patent states "the tactile sensor arrangements may be utilized as a touch screen".
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Many of these citations rely on anecdotal evidence from Bill Buxton of Bell Labs.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] However, Bill Buxton did not have much luck getting his hands on this technology.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] As he states in the citation: "Our assumption (false, as it turned out) was that the Boie technology would become available to us in the near future.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Around 1990 I took a group from Xerox to see this technology it [sic] since I felt that it would be appropriate for the user interface of our large document processors.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Although, as cited earlier, Johnson is credited with developing the first finger operated capacitive and resistive touchscreens in 1965, these worked by directly touching wires across the front of the screen.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Stumpe and Beck developed a self-capacitance touchscreen in 1972, and a mutual capacitance touchscreen in 1977.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Both these devices could only sense the finger by direct touch or through a thin insulating film.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] This was 11 microns thick according to Stumpe's 1977 report.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Fujitsu released a touch pad for the Micro 16 to accommodate the complexity of kanji characters, which were stored as tiled graphics.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] A graphic touch tablet was released for the Sega AI Computer.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Touch-sensitive control-display units (CDUs) were evaluated for commercial aircraft flight decks in the early 1980s.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Initial research showed that a touch interface would reduce pilot workload as the crew could then select waypoints, functions and actions, rather than be "head down" typing latitudes, longitudes, and waypoint codes on a keyboard.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] An effective integration of this technology was aimed at helping flight crews maintain a high level of situational awareness of all major aspects of the vehicle operations including the flight path, the functioning of various aircraft systems, and moment-to-moment human interactions.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The finished device was dubbed the ECC for "Electronic Control Center", a digital computer and software control system hardwired to various peripheral sensors, servomechanisms, solenoids, antenna and a monochrome CRT touchscreen that functioned both as display and sole method of input.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The ECC replaced the traditional mechanical stereo, fan, heater and air conditioner controls and displays, and was capable of providing very detailed and specific information about the vehicle's cumulative and current operating status in real time.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Sega released the Terebi Oekaki, also known as the Sega Graphic Board, for the SG-1000 video game console and SC-3000 home computer.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] It consisted of a plastic pen and a plastic board with a transparent window where pen presses are detected.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] It was used primarily with a drawing software application.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The University of Toronto group, including Bill Buxton, developed a multi-touch tablet that used capacitance rather than bulky camera-based optical sensing systems (see History of multi-touch).
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The first commercially available graphical point-of-sale (POS) software was demonstrated on the 16-bit Atari 520ST color computer.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] It featured a color touchscreen widget-driven interface.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The ViewTouch POS software was first shown by its developer, Gene Mosher, at the Atari Computer demonstration area of the Fall COMDEX expo in 1986.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Casio launched the Casio PB-1000 pocket computer with a touchscreen consisting of a 4×4 matrix, resulting in 16 touch areas in its small LCD graphic screen.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Touchscreens had a bad reputation of being imprecise until 1988.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Most user-interface books would state that touchscreen selections were limited to targets larger than the average finger.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] At the time, selections were done in such a way that a target was selected as soon as the finger came over it, and the corresponding action was performed immediately.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Errors were common, due to parallax or calibration problems, leading to user frustration.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] "Lift-off strategy" was introduced by researchers at the University of Maryland Human–Computer Interaction Lab (HCIL).
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] As users touch the screen, feedback is provided as to what will be selected: users can adjust the position of the finger, and the action takes place only when the finger is lifted off the screen.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] This allowed the selection of small targets, down to a single pixel on a 640×480 Video Graphics Array (VGA) screen (a standard of that time).
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] From April to October 1988, the city of Brisbane, Australia hosted Expo 88, whose theme was "leisure in the age of technology".
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] To support the event and provide information to expo visitors, Telecom Australia (now Telstra) erected 8 kiosks around the expo site with a total of 56 touch screen information consoles, being specially modified Sony Videotex Workstations.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Each system was also equipped with a videodisc player, speakers, and a 20 MB hard drive.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] In order to keep up-to-date information during the event, the database of visitor information was updated and remotely transferred to the computer terminals each night.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Using the touch screens, visitors were able to find information about the exposition's rides, attractions, performances, facilities, and the surrounding areas.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Visitors could also select between information displayed in English and Japanese; a reflection of Australia's overseas tourist market in the 1980s.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] It is worth noting that Telecom's Expo Info system was based on an earlier system employed at Expo 86 in Vancouver, Canada.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] (1990) gave a review of academic research on single and multi-touch human–computer interaction of the time, describing gestures such as rotating knobs, adjusting sliders, and swiping the screen to activate a switch (or a U-shaped gesture for a toggle switch).
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The HCIL team developed and studied small touchscreen keyboards (including a study that showed users could type at 25 wpm on a touchscreen keyboard), aiding their introduction on mobile devices.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] They also designed and implemented multi-touch gestures such as selecting a range of a line, connecting objects, and a "tap-click" gesture to select while maintaining location with another finger.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] HCIL demonstrated a touchscreen slider, which was later cited as prior art in the lock screen patent litigation between Apple and other touchscreen mobile phone vendors (in relation to U.S. patent 7,657,849).
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] From 1991 to 1992, the Sun Star7 prototype PDA implemented a touchscreen with inertial scrolling.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Bob Boie of AT&T Bell Labs, patented a simple mouse or keypad that capacitively sensed just one finger through a thin insulator.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Although not claimed or even mentioned in the patent, this technology could potentially have been used as a capacitance touchscreen.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] IBM released the IBM Simon, which is the first touchscreen phone.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] An early attempt at a handheld game console with touchscreen controls was Sega's intended successor to the Game Gear, though the device was ultimately shelved and never released due to the expensive cost of touchscreen technology in the early 1990s.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Apple patents its multi-touch capacitive touchscreen for mobile devices.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Touchscreens were not popularly used for video games until the release of the Nintendo DS in 2004.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The first mobile phone with a capacitive touchscreen was LG Prada, released in May 2007 (which was before the first iPhone released).
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] By 2009, touchscreen-enabled mobile phones were becoming trendy and quickly gaining popularity in both basic and advanced devices.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] In Quarter-4 2009 for the first time, a majority of smartphones (i.e. not all mobile phones) shipped with touchscreens over non-touch.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Until recently, most consumer touchscreens could only sense one point of contact at a time, and few have had the capability to sense how hard one is touching.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] This has changed with the commercialization of multi-touch technology, and the Apple Watch being released with a force-sensitive display in April 2015.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] There are a number of touchscreen technologies, with different methods of sensing touch.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] A resistive touchscreen panel is composed of several thin layers, the most important of which are two transparent electrically resistive layers facing each other with a thin gap between them.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The top layer (the layer that is touched) has a coating on the underside surface; just beneath it is a similar resistive layer on top of its substrate.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] One layer has conductive connections along its sides, while the other along the top and bottom.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] A voltage is applied to one layer and sensed by the other.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] When an object, such as a fingertip or stylus tip, presses down onto the outer surface, the two layers touch to become connected at that point.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The panel then behaves as a pair of voltage dividers, one axis at a time.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] By rapidly switching between each layer, the position of pressure on the screen can be detected.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Resistive touch is used in restaurants, factories, and hospitals due to its high tolerance for liquids and contaminants.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] A major benefit of resistive-touch technology is its low cost.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Additionally, they may be used with gloves on, or by using anything rigid as a finger substitute, as only sufficient pressure is necessary for the touch to be sensed.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Disadvantages include the need to press down, and a risk of damage by sharp objects.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Resistive touchscreens also suffer from poorer contrast, due to having additional reflections (i.e. glare) from the layers of material placed over the screen.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] This type of touchscreen has been used by Nintendo in the DS family, the 3DS family, and the Wii U GamePad.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Due to their simple structure, with very few inputs, resistive touchscreens are mainly used for single touch operation, although some two touch versions (often described as multi-touch) are available.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] However, there are some true multi-touch resistive touchscreens available.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] These need many more inputs, and rely on x/y multiplexing to keep the I/O count down.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] One example of a true multi-touch resistive touchscreen can detect 10 fingers at the same time.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] These are possibly split 34 x inputs / 46 y outputs, forming a standard 3:4 aspect ratio touchscreen with 1564 x/y intersecting touch sensing nodes.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Surface acoustic wave (SAW) technology uses ultrasonic waves that pass over the touchscreen panel.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] When the panel is touched, a portion of the wave is absorbed.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The change in ultrasonic waves is processed by the controller to determine the position of the touch event.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Surface acoustic wave touchscreen panels can be damaged by outside elements.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Contaminants on the surface can also interfere with the functionality of the touchscreen.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] SAW devices have a wide range of applications, including delay lines, filters, correlators and DC to DC converters.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] A capacitive touchscreen panel consists of an insulator, such as glass, coated with a transparent conductor, such as indium tin oxide (ITO).
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] As the human body is also an electrical conductor, touching the surface of the screen results in a distortion of the screen's electrostatic field, measurable as a change in capacitance.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Different technologies may be used to determine the location of the touch.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The location is then sent to the controller for processing.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Some touchscreens use silver instead of ITO, as ITO causes several environmental problems due to the use of indium.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The controller is typically a complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor (CMOS) application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) chip, which in turn usually sends the signals to a CMOS digital signal processor (DSP) for processing.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] In addition to indium tin oxide (ITO), other transparent conductive materials have been used for capacitive touch sensors.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] These include patterned metal-mesh electrodes and silver nanowire networks, which can offer lower electrical resistance and improved scalability for larger-format or flexible touch panels.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Such alternatives are often explored where higher conductivity or mechanical flexibility is required.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Unlike a resistive touchscreen, some capacitive touchscreens cannot be used to detect a finger through electrically insulating material, such as gloves.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] This disadvantage especially affects usability in consumer electronics, such as touch tablet PCs and capacitive smartphones in cold weather when people may be wearing gloves.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] It can be overcome with a special capacitive stylus, or a special-application glove with an embroidered patch of conductive thread allowing electrical contact with the user's fingertip.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] A low-quality switching-mode power supply unit with an accordingly unstable, noisy voltage may temporarily interfere with the precision, accuracy and sensitivity of capacitive touch screens.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Projected capacitive touchscreens can detect a finger which is near the screen without necessarily touching it.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] This allows for more accurate measurements, multi-touch support, and allows sensing through light gloves.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Because projected capacitive systems use a solid glass surface rather than flexible top films, they generally offer improved scratch resistance and long-term mechanical durability compared to resistive touchscreens.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Some capacitive display manufacturers continue to develop thinner and more accurate touchscreens.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Those for mobile devices are now being produced with 'in-cell' technology, such as in Samsung's Super AMOLED screens, that eliminates a layer by building the capacitors inside the display itself.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] This type of touchscreen reduces the visible distance between the user's finger and what the user is touching on the screen, reducing the thickness and weight of the display, which is desirable in smartphones.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] A simple parallel-plate capacitor has two conductors separated by a dielectric layer.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Most of the energy in this system is concentrated directly between the plates.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Some of the energy spills over into the area outside the plates, and the electric field lines associated with this effect are called fringing fields.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Part of the challenge of making a practical capacitive sensor is to design a set of printed circuit traces which direct fringing fields into an active sensing area accessible to a user.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] A parallel-plate capacitor is not a good choice for such a sensor pattern.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Placing a finger near fringing electric fields adds conductive surface area to the capacitive system.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The additional charge storage capacity added by the finger is known as finger capacitance, or CF.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The capacitance of the sensor without a finger present is known as parasitic capacitance, or CP.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] In this basic technology, only one side of the insulator is coated with a conductive layer.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] A small voltage is applied to the layer, resulting in a uniform electrostatic field.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The sensor's controller can determine the location of the touch indirectly from the change in the capacitance as measured from the four corners of the panel.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] As it has no moving parts, it is moderately durable but has limited resolution, is prone to false signals from parasitic capacitive coupling, and needs calibration during manufacture.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] It is therefore most often used in simple applications such as industrial controls and kiosks.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] These fluctuations result in a lot of background noise, so a strong finger signal is required for accurate detection.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] This limits applications to those where the finger directly touches the sensing element or is sensed through a relatively thin non-conductive surface.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] An electrical signal, imposed on one electrical conductor, can be capacitively "sensed" by another electrical conductor that is in very close proximity, but electrically isolated—a feature that is exploited in mutual capacitance touchscreens.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] In a mutual capacitive sensor array, the "mutual" crossing of one electrical conductor with another electrical conductor, but with no direct electrical contact, forms a capacitor (see touchscreen#Construction).
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] High frequency voltage pulses are applied to these conductors, one at a time.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] These pulses capacitively couple to every conductor that intersects it.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Bringing a finger or conductive stylus close to the surface of the sensor changes the local electrostatic field, which in turn reduces the capacitance between these intersecting conductors.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Any significant change in the strength of the signal sensed is used to determine if a finger is present or not at an intersection.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The capacitance change at every intersection on the grid can be measured to accurately determine one or more touch locations.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Mutual capacitance allows multi-touch operation where multiple fingers, palms or styli can be accurately tracked at the same time.The greater the number of intersections, the better the touch resolution and the more independent fingers that can be detected.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] This indicates a distinct advantage of diagonal wiring over standard x/y wiring, since diagonal wiring creates nearly twice the number of intersections.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] A 30 i/o, 16×14 x/y array, for example, would have 224 of these intersections / capacitors, and a 30 i/o diagonal lattice array could have 435 intersections.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Each trace of an x/y mutual capacitance array only has one function, it is either an input or an output.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The horizontal traces may be transmitters while the vertical traces are sensors, or vice versa.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Self-capacitance sensors can have the same layout as mutual capacitance sensors, but, with self-capacitance all the traces usually operate independently, with no interaction between different traces.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Along with several other methods, the extra capacitive load of a finger on a trace electrode may be measured by a current meter, or by the change in frequency of an RC oscillator.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Traces are sensed, one after the other until all the traces have been sensed.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] A finger may be detected anywhere along the whole length of a trace (even "off-screen"), but there is no indication where the finger is along that trace.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] If, however, a finger is also detected along another intersecting trace, then it is assumed that the finger position is at the intersection of the two traces.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] This allows for the speedy and accurate detection of a single finger.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Although mutual capacitance is simpler for multi-touch, multi-touch can be achieved using self-capacitance.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Self-capacitive touch screen layers are used on mobile phones such as the Sony Xperia Sola, the Samsung Galaxy S4, Galaxy Note 3, Galaxy S5, and Galaxy Alpha.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Self-capacitance is far more sensitive than mutual capacitance and is mainly used for single touch, simple gesturing and proximity sensing where the finger does not even have to touch the glass surface.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Mutual capacitance is mainly used for multitouch applications.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Many touchscreen manufacturers use both self and mutual capacitance technologies in the same product, thereby combining their individual benefits.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Capacitive touchscreens do not necessarily need to be operated by a finger, but until recently the special styli required could be quite expensive to purchase.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The cost of this technology has fallen greatly in recent years and capacitive styli are now widely available for a nominal charge, and often given away free with mobile accessories.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] These consist of an electrically conductive shaft with a soft conductive rubber tip, thereby resistively connecting the fingers to the tip of the stylus.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Capacitive touchscreen technology can be used for ultra-high resolution sensing, such as fingerprint sensing.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Fingerprint sensors require a micro-capacitor spacing of about 44 to 50 microns.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] An infrared touchscreen uses an array of X-Y infrared LED and photodetector pairs around the edges of the screen to detect a disruption in the pattern of LED beams.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] These LED beams cross each other in vertical and horizontal patterns.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] This helps the sensors pick up the exact location of the touch.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] A major benefit of such a system is that it can detect essentially any opaque object including a finger, gloved finger, stylus or pen.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] It is generally used in outdoor applications and POS systems that cannot rely on a conductor (such as a bare finger) to activate the touchscreen.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Unlike capacitive touchscreens, infrared touchscreens do not require any patterning on the glass which increases durability and optical clarity of the overall system.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Infrared touchscreens are sensitive to dirt and dust that can interfere with the infrared beams, and suffer from parallax in curved surfaces and accidental press when the user hovers a finger over the screen while searching for the item to be selected.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] A translucent acrylic sheet is used as a rear-projection screen to display information.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The edges of the acrylic sheet are illuminated by infrared LEDs, and infrared cameras are focused on the back of the sheet.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Objects placed on the sheet are detectable by the cameras.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] When the sheet is touched by the user, frustrated total internal reflection results in leakage of infrared light which peaks at the points of maximum pressure, indicating the user's touch location.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Microsoft's PixelSense tablets used this technology.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Optical touchscreens are a relatively modern development in touchscreen technology, in which two or more image sensors (such as CMOS sensors) are placed around the edges (mostly the corners) of the screen.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Infrared backlights are placed in the sensor's field of view on the opposite side of the screen.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] A touch blocks some lights from the sensors, and the location and size of the touching object can be calculated (see visual hull).
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] This technology is growing in popularity due to its scalability, versatility, and affordability for larger touchscreens.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Introduced in 2002 by 3M, this system detects a touch by measuring the piezoelectric effect — the voltage generated when mechanical force is applied to a material — that occurs when a glass substrate is touched.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Complex algorithms interpret this information and provide the actual location of the touch.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The technology is unaffected by dust and other outside elements, including scratches.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Since there is no need for additional elements on screen, it also claims to provide excellent optical clarity.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Any object can be used to generate touch events, including gloved fingers.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] A downside is that after the initial touch, the system cannot detect a motionless finger.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] However, for the same reason, resting objects do not disrupt touch recognition.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The key to this technology is that a touch at any one position on the surface generates a sound wave in the substrate which then produces a unique combined signal as measured by three or more tiny transducers attached to the edges of the touchscreen.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The digitized signal is compared to a list corresponding to every position on the surface, determining the touch location.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] A moving touch is tracked by rapid repetition of this process.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Extraneous and ambient sounds are ignored since they do not match any stored sound profile.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The technology differs from other sound-based technologies by using a simple look-up method rather than expensive signal-processing hardware.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] As with the dispersive signal technology system, a motionless finger cannot be detected after the initial touch.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] However, for the same reason, the touch recognition is not disrupted by any resting objects.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The technology was created by SoundTouch Ltd in the early 2000s, as described by the patent family EP1852772, and introduced to the market by Tyco International's Elo division in 2006 as Acoustic Pulse Recognition.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The touchscreen used by Elo is made of ordinary glass, giving good durability and optical clarity.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The technology usually retains accuracy with scratches and dust on the screen.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The technology is also well suited to displays that are physically larger.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The development of multi-touch screens facilitated the tracking of more than one finger on the screen; thus, operations that require more than one finger are possible.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] These devices also allow multiple users to interact with the touchscreen simultaneously.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] With the growing use of touchscreens, the cost of touchscreen technology is routinely absorbed into the products that incorporate it and is nearly eliminated.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Touchscreen technology has demonstrated reliability and is found in airplanes, automobiles, gaming consoles, machine control systems, appliances, and handheld display devices including cellphones; the touchscreen market for mobile devices was projected to produce US$5 billion by 2009.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The ability to accurately point on the screen itself is also advancing with the emerging graphics tablet-screen hybrids.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Polyvinylidene fluoride (PVDF) plays a major role in this innovation due its high piezoelectric properties, which allow the tablet to sense pressure, making such things as digital painting behave more like paper and pencil.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] TapSense, announced in October 2011, allows touchscreens to distinguish what part of the hand was used for input, such as the fingertip, knuckle and fingernail.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] This could be used in a variety of ways, for example, to copy and paste, to capitalize letters, to activate different drawing modes, etc.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] For touchscreens to be effective input devices, users must be able to accurately select targets and avoid accidental selection of adjacent targets.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The design of touchscreen interfaces should reflect technical capabilities of the system, ergonomics, cognitive psychology and human physiology.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Guidelines for touchscreen designs were first developed in the 2000s, based on early research and actual use of older systems, typically using infrared grids—which were highly dependent on the size of the user's fingers.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] These guidelines are less relevant for the bulk of modern touch devices which use capacitive or resistive touch technology.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] From the mid-2000s, makers of operating systems for smartphones have promulgated standards, but these vary between manufacturers, and allow for significant variation in size based on technology changes, so are unsuitable from a human factors perspective.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Much more important is the accuracy humans have in selecting targets with their finger or a pen stylus.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The accuracy of user selection varies by position on the screen: users are most accurate at the center, less so at the left and right edges, and least accurate at the top edge and especially the bottom edge.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The R95 accuracy (required radius for 95% target accuracy) varies from 7 mm (0.28 in) in the center to 12 mm (0.47 in) in the lower corners.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Users are subconsciously aware of this, and take more time to select targets which are smaller or at the edges or corners of the touchscreen.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] This user inaccuracy is a result of parallax, visual acuity and the speed of the feedback loop between the eyes and fingers.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The precision of the human finger alone is much, much higher than this, so when assistive technologies are provided—such as on-screen magnifiers—users can move their finger (once in contact with the screen) with precision as small as 0.1 mm (0.004 in).
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Users of handheld and portable touchscreen devices hold them in a variety of ways, and routinely change their method of holding and selection to suit the position and type of input.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] While two-thumb tapping is encountered rarely (1–3%) for many general interactions, it is used for 41% of typing interaction.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] In addition, devices are often placed on surfaces (desks or tables) and tablets especially are used in stands.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The user may point, select or gesture in these cases with their finger or thumb, and vary use of these methods.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] A related study investigated how users interact with touchscreen laptops in office settings.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] It identified four common arm postures—freehand, arm resting, edge support, and top-edge support—and found that users often combined touch with other input methods.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The study reported limited adoption of touch interaction during everyday work, mainly due to ergonomic strain, screen stability issues, and inconsistent application support.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Touchscreens are often used with haptic response systems.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] A common example of this technology is the vibratory feedback provided when a button on the touchscreen is tapped.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Haptics are used to improve the user's experience with touchscreens by providing simulated tactile feedback, and can be designed to react immediately, partly countering on-screen response latency.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] On top of this, a study conducted in 2013 by Boston College explored the effects that touchscreens haptic stimulation had on triggering psychological ownership of a product.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Their research concluded that a touchscreens ability to incorporate high amounts of haptic involvement resulted in customers feeling more endowment to the products they were designing or buying.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The study also reported that consumers using a touchscreen were willing to accept a higher price point for the items they were purchasing.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Touchscreen technology has become integrated into many aspects of customer service industry in the 21st century.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The restaurant industry is a good example of touchscreen implementation into this domain.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Chain restaurants such as Taco Bell, Panera Bread, and McDonald's offer touchscreens as an option when customers are ordering items off the menu.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] While the addition of touchscreens is a development for this industry, customers may choose to bypass the touchscreen and order from a traditional cashier.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] To take this a step further, a restaurant in Bangalore has attempted to completely automate the ordering process.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Customers sit down to a table embedded with touchscreens and order off an extensive menu.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Once the order is placed it is sent electronically to the kitchen.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] These types of touchscreens fit under the Point of Sale (POS) systems mentioned in the lead section.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Extended use of gestural interfaces without the ability of the user to rest their arm is referred to as "gorilla arm".
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] It can result in fatigue, and even repetitive stress injury when routinely used in a work setting.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Certain early pen-based interfaces required the operator to work in this position for much of the workday.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Allowing the user to rest their hand or arm on the input device or a frame around it is a solution for this in many contexts.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] This phenomenon is often cited as an example of movements to be minimized by proper ergonomic design.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Unsupported touchscreens are still fairly common in applications such as ATMs and data kiosks, but are not an issue as the typical user only engages for brief and widely spaced periods.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Touchscreens can suffer from the problem of fingerprints on the display.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] This can be mitigated by the use of materials with optical coatings designed to reduce the visible effects of fingerprint oils.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Most modern smartphones have oleophobic coatings, which lessen the amount of oil residue.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Another option is to install a matte-finish anti-glare screen protector, which creates a slightly roughened surface that does not easily retain smudges.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Capacitive touchscreens rarely work when the user wears gloves.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] The thickness of the glove and the material they are made of play a significant role on that and the ability of a touchscreen to pick up a touch.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] Some devices have a mode which increases the sensitivity of the touchscreen.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] This allows the touchscreen to be used more reliably with gloves, but can also result in unreliable and phantom inputs.
[src:capacitive-sensing/touchscreen] However, thin gloves such as medical gloves are thin enough for users to wear when using touchscreens; mostly applicable to medical technology and machines.
